<DOC><DOCNO> AP880315-0283 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2102EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-NewComputers     03-15 0274</FIRST><SECOND>AM-New Computers,0283</SECOND><HEAD>Unisys, ATandamp;T, NCR Introduce Computers; IBM Shows Software</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Unisys Corp., ATandamp;T and NCR Corp. unveiledcomputers Tuesday and IBM said it was making a version of thepopular Unix operating system available on its largest mainframes.   The announcement by International Business Machines Corp. wasanother acknowledgment of the growing popularity of Unix, a kind ofinternal traffic cop for computers that was invented by AmericanTelephone andamp; Telegraph Co.   IBM's version of Unix is called AIX and is now available oncomputers ranging from the top of its personal computer line allthe way up to its mainframes. Each computer also has its ownoperating system.   Unisys announced additions to its 1100 family of mainframecomputers. It said the 2200-400 family was a group of mid-rangemainframes offering a four-fold improvement in the amount ofperformance for the price along with 70 percent less space, powerand cooling needs.   The Unisys computers, including some data storage and otherextras, will range in price from $178,000 to $953,000 and will beavailable between the end of this year and the second half of 1989.   NCR introduced the System 10000, which it called a family ofmid-range, multi-user computers ranging in price from $31,000 to$227,000. All will be available this year. The computers areintended to have terminals hooked up to them.   ATandamp;T announced a new personal computer, the 6300 WorkGroupSystem, that runs Microsoft Corp.'s DOS operating system. It saidthe computer ranges in price from $1,400 to $2,100 and is availablenow. ATandamp;T also sells more powerful personal computers ranging inprice up to $10,400.</TEXT></DOC>